```js
class Q{
  constructor(){this.a=[];this.b=[];}
  push(x){this.a.push(x);}                          // O(1)
  pop(){
    if(this.b.length===0)                           // refill only when b is empty
      while(this.a.length) this.b.push(this.a.pop()); // reverse a into b
    return this.b.pop();                            // O(1) amortized
  }
}
```

Trace (FIFO check): push 1,2,3 → `a=[1,2,3] b=[]`; pop→ refill `b=[3,2,1]`, returns **1**; pop→ **2**; pop→ **3**; push 4,5; pop→ refill `b=[5,4]`, returns **4**. Output `1,2,3,4` = FIFO. ✓ (hand-traced, not run)

Amortized check: every element is pushed to `a` once, moved to `b` once, popped once — 3 touches over its life. So n pops cost O(n) total → **O(1) amortized** per pop. Worst-case single pop is O(k) only when `b` is empty and k items must move. ✓ (counting argument)

Decision trail: chose the empty-`b`-refill guard over refilling on every pop, because refilling only when `b` empties is what makes each element move once and gives the amortized bound — backed by the counting argument above. Verified by hand-trace, not execution.
